ew.\n- Development: not open to new ideas suggests limited growth.\n\nB:\n- Reliability: very conscientious, handles stress well.\n- Technical: weather assessment, computer skills.\n- Calmness: handles stress well.\n- Decision-making: not explicit but conscientiousness suggests good.\n- Teamwork/communication: makes nasty remarks, weak memory for numbers (could affect communication), but no explicit teamwork strengths.\n- Development: no mention of willingness to develop.\n\nC:\n- Reliability: quick correct decisions, keeps calm in crisis, concern for others? Not in list but earlier maybe. Not in final list. But we have \"keeps calm in a crisis\" and \"understands complicated technology\". Also \"excellent attention skills\"? Not in final list. We'll stick to given.\n- Technical: understands complicated technology.\n- Calmness: keeps calm in crisis.\n- Decision-making: quick correct decisions.\n- Teamwork/communication: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric.\n- Development: not willing to further education.\n\nD:\n- Reliability: takes responsibility seriously, solves problems, concentration.\n- Technical: problem solving, concentration, respond to unexpected events.\n- Calmness: not explicit, but hot temper is a weakness.\n- Decision-making: responds adequately to unexpected events.\n- Teamwork/communication: no info, and we asked and got none. Also know-it-all, hot temper may hinder.\n- Development: no mention.\n\nNow weigh. Which candidate best overall? B has strong technical (weather, computer) and stress handling, conscientiousness. Weakness: nasty remarks, weak memory for numbers. C has strong decision-making, calmness, technical understanding, but communication difficulty and egocentric, not willing to develop. D has strong responsibility and problem solving, but hot temper and arrogance, unknown teamwork. A has anticipation and spatial vision, leadership, but show-off, not open to new ideas.\n\nLong-distance flights require: reliability, ability to handle fatigue, stress, weather, navigation, crew coordination. Weather assessment is crucial. B's weather skill is a big plus. Also computer skills for navigation. Stress handling is vital. Conscientiousness suggests reliability. Communication issues (nasty remarks) could be problematic but maybe manageable.\n\nC's quick correct decisions and calmness are also vital. However communication difficulty and egocentric may be more severe for crew coordination. Also lack of willingness to further education could affect long-term.\n\nD's hot temper could be dangerous under stress. Lack of teamwork info is concerning.\n\nA's anticipation and spatial vision are valuable for navigation, but show-off and not open to new ideas could affect crew and adaptability.\n\nThus B seems strongest overall, despite interpersonal flaw. However we must consider that we have no info about B's reliability beyond conscientiousness; but that's strong. Also B's weak memory for numbers could affect flight calculations. But maybe mitigated by computer skills.\n\nC's reliability is implied by quick correct decisions and calmness, but communication issues may be severe.\n\nGiven the tradeoffs, I think B is still best. However we need to consider uncertainties: we lack info about B's teamwork beyond nasty remarks; we lack info about C's technical depth beyond understanding technology; we lack info about D's teamwork; we lack info about A's stress handling.\n\nThus I might provisionally prefer B, but note uncertainties. However Agent 1 prefers C, Agent 3 prefers B. I need to state my own provisional preference. I can choose B or C. I think B is slightly better due to weather assessment and stress handling, which are critical for long-distance. So I will vote B.\n\nNow produce public message summarizing evidence, mention others' votes, tradeoffs, uncertainties, what would change my vote."}
